questions.scenario:
You are debugging a production issue where a distributed saga orchestrator calls a Spring-managed microservice. The service updates a local database and then publishes an event to an external Kafka broker. If the Kafka publish fails with a `RuntimeException`, the local database transaction does not roll back, leaving the system in an inconsistent state. Below is the relevant code snippet:

java
@Service
public class OrderService {
    @Autowired
    private OrderRepository orderRepository;
    @Autowired
    private KafkaTemplate<String, Object> kafkaTemplate;

    public void createOrder(Order order) {
        saveAndNotify(order);
    }

    @Transactional(rollbackFor = Exception.class)
    public void saveAndNotify(Order order) {
        orderRepository.save(order);
        kafkaTemplate.send("order-topic", order);
    }
}

You are debugging a production issue where a high-throughput, reactive Spring WebFlux gateway experiences sudden thread starvation and high latency during a downstream microservice outage. Your team implemented a fallback path using `onErrorResume` to fetch data from a legacy relational database using JDBC. Below is the code snippet:

java
public Mono<Response> getServiceData(String id) {
    return webClient.get()
        .uri("/data/" + id)
        .retrieve()
        .bodyToMono(Response.class)
        .onErrorResume(ex -> Mono.just(jdbcCacheRepository.findById(id))); 
}
